One of the victims of GE’s takeover bids was RCA. The company’s flawed diversification strategy in the 1970s had left it deep in debt, and the early 1980s saw the company desperately struggling to cut costs while “fending off a swarm of corporate raiders” (
 
  92
 ). A new CEO refocused the firm on its core competency, selling off its solar division to Solarex, which subsequently became a subsidiary of Amoco (
 
  93
 ).
